Incident.Summary: Assist TCSO with possible fatal overdose

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
On 11/2/2023 at approximately 1630 hours, I, Cpl. Royer with the Talbot County Sheriff’s Office, currently assigned to the Talbot County Drug Task Force, was notified by Sgt. Timms with the Talbot County Sheriff's Office Patrol Division, about a possible overdose death that occurred at 13542 Moreland Lane Queen Anne, Talbot County, Maryland.  Sgt. Timms informed me that the deceased was identified as Chad Benjamin Coultas (W/M, DOB: 4/12/1988) and they were located in an apartment behind the main residence.  

    Upon my arrival, I made contact with DFC. Genna with the Talbot County Sheriff's Office Criminal Investigations Division outside of the apartment and Sgt. Timms inside of the apartment, where I also observed Chad slouched on the couch.  Sgt. Timms advised that no obvious signs of injury were observed to Chad’s body and that he was prescribed a plethora of medications due to multiple illnesses and health conditions. 

    I observed a black Samsung cellular phone on the kitchen table and was advised by Sgt. Timms that the phone belonged to Chad.  Chad’s mother, Darla Maxine Coultas (W/F, DOB: 11/8/1961), provided me with the passcode to Chad’s phone (1988).  Chad’s father, Vernon James Coultas Sr. (W/M, DOB: 2/8/1958) advised me there was a suspicious text message between Chad and “Ricky Gaines” on the phone.  I located a text message conversation between Chad and a contact named “Capt. Dingling Ganes with a phone number of 410-829-7454” beginning on November 1, 2023 at 1:51pm EST.  The context of the conversation went as follows:
  • 1:51pm from Chad to Capt. Dingling Ganes – “What up bud you think you can do 2 caps for 17 when you get off slide out my way bunk.”
  • 4:25pm from Chad to Capt. Dingling Ganes – “When you head my way let me know when your 5 or 10 out im just going to met you on road fuck my parents lol.”
  • 4:26pm from Chad to Capt. Dingling Ganes – “Just makes it easyer.”
  • 5:29pm from Capt. Dingling Ganes to Chad – “I’m like ten min out”
  • 5:30pm from Chad to Capt. Dingling Ganes – “(thumbs up emoji) you will see me walking”
  • 5:36pm from Capt. Dingling Ganes to Chad – “You heading toward rofo?”
  • 5:37pm from Chad to Capt. Dingling Ganes – “Post office by next to wood mill”
  • 5:37pm from Capt. Dingling Ganes to Chad – “Ok” 
    In the above conversation, I believe Chad is asking "Capt. Dingling Ganes" to sell him two capsules of heroin for $17.  I believe Chad wants to meet "Capt. Dingling Ganes" at or near the post office due to not wanting his parents to see making contact with his drug supplier.  I know through my training, knowledge and experience that "caps" are common street terminology for gelatin capsules, used to package heroin/fentanyl, which are commonly purchased in Baltimore City, Maryland at a much lower price than on the Eastern Shore of Maryland.  
    
    A free open-source reverse phone number search was conducted which revealed 410-829-7454 belonged to Richard Gaines. The phone was subsequently seized by DFC. Genna and submitted to the Talbot County Sheriff’s Office Property Room pending a data extraction.

    Vernon advised me that at approximately 1730 hours, he observed Chad exit a red GMC pickup truck near the end of his driveway, which was being operated by “Ricky Gaines”.  Vernon advised that he has told Chad numerous times that “Ricky Gaines” is not allowed on the property and that he doesn’t like Chad hanging out with “Ricky” due to Chad’s prior history of CDS abuse.  Vernon stated Chad was doing a good job staying clean until “Ricky” started showing up about a month ago.

    DFC. Genna and I conducted a search of the apartment, where a portion of a gelatin capsule was located on the floor near the stove.  DFC. Genna also located a white powdery substance in a folded piece of paper, packaged in a clear plastic wrapper, inside of Chad’s tri-fold wallet. Based on my training, knowledge and experience, I believe the white powdery substance to be Methamphetamine.  

    A family friend was on location (member of the fire department) who was familiar with “Ricky Gaines” and positively identified “Ricky” as Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 7/2/1987.  The family friend also advised that the red GMC pickup truck is “Ricky’s” fathers truck (Richard Gaines Sr.).

    Forensic Investigator (FI) Chuck Ward, of the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner, arrived on scene to examine Chad’s body. FI Ward observed possible needle marks to the elbow pit of Chad’s left arm. FI Ward also noted that rigor mortis was fully set. Chad was subsequently taken to the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner in Baltimore, Maryland for autopsy and toxicology.

    On Friday, November 3, 2023, I conducted a search through the Maryland Motor Vehicle Administration for any vehicles listed to Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 7/2/1987, which revealed that the last registered vehicle in his name expired in 2020.  I then searched for vehicles registered to Richard Gaines Sr, which revealed that a 2008 GMC truck with the registration of 6FG3142, which was current and believed that was the vehicle being operated by Richard Gaines Jr. on November 2, 2023.

    On Friday, November 3, 2023, I requested the Eastern Shore Information Center (ESIC) perform a search of the License Plate Reader (LPR) database regarding Maryland registration 6FG3142, from August 1, 2023 to November 3, 2023.  Those results revealed 11 individual trips of the red GMC pickup truck crossing the William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bay Bridge (crossing from Queen Anne’s County to Anne Arundel County) within that date range.  On two separate occasions, there were LPR hits inside Baltimore City limits.  I know that dealers and addicts from rural parts of Maryland will travel to Baltimore City to purchase capsules, also known as “Caps”, of heroin/fentanyl at approximately $6.00 per capsule, thus maximizing their profits by selling and distributing the “Caps” of heroin/fentanyl in rural areas for the upwards of $20.00 per capsule.

    On Tuesday, November 15, 2023, I requested the Administrative Technician with the Talbot County Sherif's Office conduct a driver's license check through the Maryland Motor Vehicle Administration and a criminal history check through the National Crime Information Center (NCIC) for Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 7/2/1987, which revealed the following:


(this MVA photograph was used to positively identify Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 7/2/1987)
Richard Willard Gaines Jr.               DOB: 7/2/1987 
Address:  205 Meadow View Lane Queenstown, Maryland 21658
OLN: G-520-738-886-744         Height: 6-02        Weight: 215
Status: Suspended

MARYLAND

FLORIDA


    On Thursday, November 16, 2023, I conducted a search of the Report Management System (RMS) for the Maryland State Police and Talbot County Sheriff’s Office, regarding Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 7/2/1987, that revealed the following reports of interest:
  • In November 2015, a deputy with the Talbot County Sheriff’s Office responded to a suspicious person call in Easton, Talbot County, Maryland, where Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 07/02/1987 was identified as the subject, who was located inside of a vehicle.  While the deputy was speaking with Gaines, they observed a metal spoon on Gaines’ lap, which had apparent burn marks on the bottom.  The deputy order Gaines out of the vehicle and conducted a probable cause search of the vehicle.  The deputy located a ripped/folded piece of paper containing a brown, powdery substance, suspected to be Heroin, two (2) small plastic baggies containing a brown, powdery substance of suspected Heroin and two (2) hypodermic needles wrapped up in a blue microfiber towel.  The trooper placed Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 07/02/1987 under arrest for CDS Possession-not Marijuana and CDS possession paraphernalia.
 
  • In September 2019, a trooper with the Maryland State Police Centreville Barrack conducted a traffic stop on a vehicle in Chester, Queen Anne’s County, Maryland, where Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 07/02/1987 was identified as the driver and sole occupant.  The trooper observed a syringe in Gaines’ hand and conducted a probable cause search of the vehicle.  Prior to Gaines exiting the vehicle, he handed the trooper a gelatin capsule containing suspected heroin, along with the syringe the trooper had previously observed.  The trooper placed Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 07/02/1987 under arrest for CDS: Possess- Not Marijuana and CDS: Possess Paraphernalia.
    In another report, not pertaining to controlled dangerous substances, Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 07/02/1987 was interviewed in June 2023 by the Maryland State police as a witness regarding his roomate's, Paul Garrett, stolen vehicle.  During that interview, Richard Willard Gaines Jr, W/M, DOB: 07/02/1987 provided his address of 10209 Unionville Road Easton, Talbot County, Maryland.

    This incident remains open further investigation.

Incident Status: OPEN
